<subSubSection lastPageId="228" lastPageNumber="229" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="227.[151,1437,1194,2011]" lastBlockId="228.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="228" lastPageNumber="229" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1914,1939]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1964" box="[662,790,1915,1939]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Anisepyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venustus">
<emphasis box="[662,790,1915,1939]" italics="true" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">A. venustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the mandible very narrow; the antenna serrate, not elongate, and with long setae; the clypeus with the clypeal carina higher than frons level; the circumocular suture present; the metapectal-propodeal complex longer than wide; the mesopleuron with the lower fovea closed; the metasomal segments sparsely setose; the paramere wide; the basivolsella straight; the cuspis with the arms very short; and the aedeagus with the basal portion angled and wide, the apical portion very wide and as long as the basal portion, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1964" box="[419,549,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Anisepyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="228" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venustus">
<emphasis box="[419,549,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="228" pageNumber="229">A. venustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mandible narrow; the antenna not elongate, filiform, and with short setae; the clypeus with the clypeal carina lower than frons level; the circumocular suture absent; the metapectalpropodeal disc long; the mesopleuron with the lower fovea opened; the metasomal segments glabrous; the paramere slender; the basivolsella with a projection at the basal portion of the inner margin; the cuspis with long arms; and the aedeagus with the basal portion convex and slender, and the apical portion slender and longer than the basal portion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
